        <h2>LED retrofitting can directly help the community</h2>
        <p>Community energy efficiency projects can directly benefit local people with more comfortable housing: money saved on lighting could be spent on heating. Warmer, drier houses are healthier, too.</p>
        <p>With community funding, those with the least can still benefit from the most modern technology.</p>
        <p>LED retrofitting gives benefit directly to those involved in the project, in addition to the usual community benefit fund.</p>

        <h2>LED retrofitting doesn’t rely on government subsidies</h2>
        <p>Energy efficiency projects pay for themselves without the need for subsidies, CSR or charity money. That makes them resilient and scalable.</p>
        <p>A successful 25 home pilot could scale to thousands, independent of the whims of the latest policy, tariff or tax break.</p>

        <h2>LED retrofitting could increase inclusion among community energy groups</h2>
        <p>Delivering energy services to local households could be a way of increasing the membership of a community energy co-operative.</p>
        <p>We imagine that groups may want to include participating households as equal voting members.</p>
        <p>That would be a truly co-operative model: local people with spare money lending to those without, connected by the genuine equality of co-operative membership.</p>

        <h2>LED retrofitting is a step towards Community Energy Services</h2>
        <p>From reading <%= link_to 'Community energy: the way forward', 'https://1010uk.org/articles/community-energy-way-forward' %> and talking to several groups, it’s clear that people are exploring a transition from generation into energy services.</p>
        <p>The services we’ve learned about are energy efficiency, battery storage, demand management and local supply.</p>

